quest_title: Hydrogen bonding is a weaker force then
explanation_txt:
Hydrogen bonds are intermolecular forces (“between-molecule”), rather than intramolecular (“within-molecule”) forces. they are much weaker than the covalent bonds holding atoms together within molecules of covalent compounds.

But, they are stronger than other intermolecular forces.

quest_title: If the ratio of the sum of \(n\) terms of two A.P.'s be \((7n+1):(4n+27)\), then the ratio of their \(11^{th} \) terms will be
explanation_txt:
Let \(S_{n} \) and \(S'_{n} \) be the sums of n terms of two A.P.'s and \(T_{11} \) and \(T'_{11} \) be the respective \(11^{th} \) terms, then:

\[\cfrac{S_{n} }{S'_{n} } =\cfrac{\cfrac{n}{2} [2a+(n-1)d]}{\cfrac{n}{2} [2a'+(n-1)d']} =\cfrac{7n+1}{4n+27} \]

\[\Rightarrow \cfrac{a+\cfrac{(n-1)}{2} d}{a'+\cfrac{(n-1)}{2} d'} =\cfrac{7n+1}{4n+27} \]

Now put \(n=21\), we get:

\(\cfrac{a+10d}{a'+10d'} =\cfrac{T_{11} }{T'_{11} } =\cfrac{148}{111} =\cfrac{4}{3} \).

Note : If ratio of sum of \(n\) terms of two A.P.'s are given in terms of \(n\) and ratio of their \(p^{th} \) terms are to be found then put \(n=2p-1\). Here we put \(n=11\times 2-1=21\).

quest_title: 0.1 mole of NaCl is added to 200ml of M/10 \(\text{AgNO\({}_{3}\)}\) solution. The molarity of nitrate ions in the solution will be
explanation_txt:
Moles of AgNO\(_3\) = 0.2*0.1 = 0.02 moles

Since 0.1 moles of NaCl > 0.02 moles of AgNO\(_3\), all AgNO\(_3\) will be converted into AgCl leaving 0.02 moles of free nitrate ions.

\(\therefore\) Molarity of free nitrate ions = \(\cfrac{0.02 \, \text{moles}}{0.2 \, \text{litres}}\) = 0.1M

\( \begin{aligned}z = \cfrac { 1 - i \sqrt { 3 } } { 1 + i \sqrt { 3 } } & = \cfrac { ( 1 - i \sqrt { 3 } ) ( 1 - i \sqrt { 3 } ) } { ( 1 + i \sqrt { 3 } ) ( 1 - i \sqrt { 3 } ) } \\ = \cfrac { 1 - 3 - 2 i \sqrt { 3 } } { 1 + 3 } & = \cfrac { - 2 - 2 i \sqrt { 3 } } { 4 } = - \cfrac { 1 } { 2 } - i \cfrac { \sqrt { 3 } } { 2 } \end{aligned} \)

Thus \( \arg ( z ) = \tan ^ { - 1 } \cfrac { y } { x } = \tan ^ { - 1 } \sqrt { 3 } = \cfrac { \pi } { 3 } = 60 ^ { \circ } \)

Since the complex number lies in III quadrant, therefore \( \arg ( z ) \text { is } 180 ^ { \circ } + 60 ^ { \circ } = 240 ^ { \circ } \)

explanation_txt:
\( m_1 = -\cfrac{a_1}{b_1} \) and \(m_2 = -\cfrac{a_2}{b_2} \)

If \( \theta \) be the angle between the lines,

\( \tan \theta = \pm \cfrac{m_1-m_2}{1+m_1m_2} \)

Putting values of \(m_1\) and \(m_2\) and simplifying,

\( \tan \theta = \pm \cfrac{a_2b_1 - a_1b_2}{a_1a_2+b_1b_2} \)

One of the value of \( \theta \) is:

\( \theta = \tan^{-1} \left( \cfrac{a_1b_2 - a_2b_1}{a_1a_2+b_1b_2} \right) \)

And using, \( \tan^{-1} x = \cot ^{-1} (1/x) \), we get the answer as (b).
